exuality, class and ethnic discrimination, and small-town hypocrisy, was more than a tawdry potboiler. Metalious's depiction of how her three central female characters come to terms with their identity as women and sexual beings anticipated second-wave feminism. More broadly, Cameron asserts, the novel was also part of a larger postwar struggle over belonging and recognition. Fictionalizing contemporary realities, Metalious pushed to the surface the hidden talk and secret rebellions of a generation no longer willing to ignore the disparities and domestic constraints of Cold War America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aBooks and readingxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aBooks and readingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLiterature and societyxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopular literaturexHistory and criticismxUnited States. 0aPopular literaturezUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aSex in literature. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aU.S. History.  apublishing industry, Grace Metalious, incest novels, sex and gender, 1950s US, women's history, sexuality, abortion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145610740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801456107423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801456107/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles